 <p id="Par65" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">To get from acceptability to sustainability for the risky policy one has to logically combine Eqs. 
  <a rid="Equ18" ref-type="" href="#Equ18">18</a> and 
  <a rid="Equ19" ref-type="" href="#Equ19">19</a>. The risky policy is sustainable only if both the prosperous and the degraded state are acceptable since it will visit both states recurrently. The safe policy is sustainable exactly where the prosperous state is acceptable since it will eventually end up and remain at the prosperous state. Supplementary Fig. 
  <a rid="MOESM1" ref-type="media" href="#MOESM1">1</a> shows an example of the acceptability division of state-parameter space and the resulting sustainability division.
 </p>
 <p id="Par66" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The division of the parameter space according the safe operating space paradigm is obvious from its definition. Only the cautious policy is a safe policy since it will eventually end up and remain in the prosperous, safe operating space state. The risky policy switches recurrently between the prosperous and the degraded which makes it, by definition, not safe.</p>
